				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Sta=
ndard division algorithm for multi-digit numbers</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">This article=
 is about elementary handwritten division. For mathematical definition and =
properties, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Division_(mathemat=
ics)" title=3D"Division (mathematics)">Division (mathematics)</a> and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_division" title=3D"Euclidean =
division">Euclidean division</a>. For software algorithms, see <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Division_algorithm" title=3D"Division algorith=
m">Division algorithm</a>. For other uses, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Long_division_(disambiguation)" class=3D"mw-redirect mw-disamb=
ig" title=3D"Long division (disambiguation)">Long division (disambiguation)=
</a>.</div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic" title=3D"Arithme=
tic">arithmetic</a>, <b>long division</b> is a standard <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Division_algorithm" title=3D"Division algorithm">divi=
sion algorithm</a> suitable for dividing multi-digit <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Hindu%E2%80%93Arabic_numeral_system" title=3D"Hindu=E2=
=80=93Arabic numeral system">Hindu-Arabic numerals</a> (<a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Positional_notation" title=3D"Positional notation">po=
sitional notation</a>) that is simple enough to perform by hand. It breaks =
down a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Division_(mathematics)" tit=
le=3D"Division (mathematics)">division</a> problem into a series of easier =
steps.
</p><p>As in all division problems, one number, called the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Division_(mathematics)" title=3D"Division (mathema=
tics)">dividend</a>, is divided by another, called the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divisor" title=3D"Divisor">divisor</a>,  producing a r=
esult called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quotient" title=
=3D"Quotient">quotient</a>. It enables computations involving arbitrarily l=
arge numbers to be performed by following a series of simple steps.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Long_division#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The abbreviated form of long divisi=
on is called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Short_division" title=
=3D"Short division">short division</a>, which is almost always used<sup cla=
ss=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=
[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" tit=
le=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references=
 to reliable sources. (November 2025)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup=
> instead of long division when the divisor has only one digit.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLong_division&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Related algorithms have existed since the 12th century.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_div=
ision#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Samawal_al-Maghribi" title=3D"A=
l-Samawal al-Maghribi">Al-Samawal al-Maghribi</a> (1125=E2=80=931174) perfo=
rmed calculations with decimal numbers that essentially require long divisi=
on, leading to infinite decimal results, but without formalizing the algori=
thm.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Long_division#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
Caldrini (1491) is the earliest printed example of long division, known as =
the <i>Danda</i> method in medieval Italy,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_division#cite_note-=
4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> and it became more practical with the introduction of decimal=
 notation for fractions by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barthol=
omaeus_Pitiscus" title=3D"Bartholomaeus Pitiscus">Pitiscus</a> (1608).
The specific algorithm in modern use was introduced by <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Briggs_(mathematician)" title=3D"Henry Briggs (m=
athematician)">Henry Briggs</a> <abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr> 1600.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Long_division#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Education">Education</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLong_division&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Education"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<table class=3D"box-Globalize plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-content ambox=
-globalize" role=3D"presentation"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"mbox-image"><div =
class=3D"mbox-image-div"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><span><img alt=3D"Globe i=
con." src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Ambo=
