data-file-height=3D"290"></span></span></div></td><td class=3D"mbox-text"><=
div class=3D"mbox-text-span">The examples and perspective in this article <=
b>may not represent a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Wi=
kiProject_Countering_systemic_bias" title=3D"Wikipedia:WikiProject Counteri=
ng systemic bias">worldwide view</a> of the subject</b>.<span class=3D"hide=
-when-compact"> You may <a class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLong_division&amp;action=3Dedit">improve this =
article</a>, discuss the issue on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Talk:Long_division" title=3D"Talk:Long division">talk page</a>, or <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Article_wizard" title=3D"Wik=
ipedia:Article wizard">create a new article</a>, as appropriate.</span>  <s=
pan class=3D"date-container"><i>(<span class=3D"date">May 2024</span>)</i><=
/span><span class=3D"hide-when-compact"><i> (<small><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal" title=3D"Help:Maintena=
nce template removal">Learn how and when to remove this message</a></small>=
)</i></span></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>Inexpensive calculators and computers have become the most common way to=
 solve division problems, eliminating a traditional <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_exercise" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mat=
hematical exercise">mathematical exercise</a> and decreasing the educationa=
l opportunity to show how to do so by paper and pencil techniques. (Interna=
lly, those devices use one of a variety of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Division_algorithm" title=3D"Division algorithm">division algorith=
ms</a>, the faster of which rely on approximations and multiplications to a=
chieve the tasks.) In North America, long division has been especially targ=
eted for de-emphasis or even elimination from the school curriculum by <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reform_mathematics" title=3D"Reform ma=
thematics">reform mathematics</a>, though it has been traditionally introdu=
ced in the 4th, 5th or even 6th grades.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_division#cite_note-6">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Method">Method</h2><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLong_division&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Method"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In English-speaking countries, long division does not use the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Division_slash" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Division slash">division slash</a> <span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=9F=A8<a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E2%88%95" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"=E2=88=95">=E2=88=95</a>=E2=9F=A9</span> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Division_sign" title=3D"Division sign">division sign</a> <spa=
n class=3D"nowrap">=E2=9F=A8=C3=B7=E2=9F=A9</span> symbols but instead cons=
tructs a <b>tableau</b>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_division#cite_note-7"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divisor" title=3D"Divisor">diviso=
r</a> is separated from the dividend by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Right_parenthesis" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Right parenthesis=
">right parenthesis</a> <span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=9F=A8<a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D")">)</a>=E2=9F=A9</=
span> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vertical_bar" title=3D"Ve=
rtical bar">vertical bar</a> <span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=9F=A8<a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vertical_bar" title=3D"Vertical bar">|</a>=E2=9F=
=A9</span>; the dividend is separated from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Quotient" title=3D"Quotient">quotient</a> by a <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vinculum_(symbol)" title=3D"Vinculum (symbol)">vi=
nculum</a> (i.e., an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Overbar" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Overbar">overbar</a>). The combination of these =
two symbols is sometimes known as a <b>long division symbol</b> or <b>divis=
ion bracket</b>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_division#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It developed=
 in the 18th century from an earlier single-line notation separating the di=
vidend from the quotient by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Left=
_parenthesis" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Left parenthesis">left parenth=
esis</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Long_division#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_divis=
ion#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The process is begun by dividing the left-most digit of the dividend=
 by the divisor.  The quotient (rounded down to an integer) becomes the fir=
st digit of the result, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Re=
mainder" title=3D"Remainder">remainder</a> is calculated (this step is nota=
ted as a subtraction).  This remainder carries forward when the process is =
repeated on the following digit of the dividend (notated as 'bringing down'=
 the next digit to the remainder).  When all digits have been processed and=
 no remainder is left, the process is complete.
</p><p>An example is shown below, representing the division of 500 by 4 (wi=
th a result of 125).
</p>
<pre>    <u> <span style=3D"color: red;">1</span><span style=3D"color: gree=
n;">2</span><span style=3D"color: blue;">5</span></u>      (Explanations)
   4)500
     <u>4</u>        ( 4 =C3=97  <span style=3D"color: red;">1</span> =3D  =
4)
     <span style=3D"color: darkorange;">1</span>0       ( 5 -  4 =3D  <span=
 style=3D"color: darkorange;">1</span>)
      <u>8</u>       ( 4 =C3=97  <span style=3D"color: green;">2</span> =3D=
  8)
      <span style=3D"color: darkcyan;">2</span>0      (10 -  8 =3D  <span s=
tyle=3D"color: darkcyan;">2</span>)
      <u>20</u>      ( 4 =C3=97  <span style=3D"color: blue;">5</span> =3D =
20)
       0      (20 - 20 =3D  0)
</pre>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Long_division.JPG" class=3D"mw-file-descripti=
on"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/L=
ong_division.JPG/250px-Long_division.JPG" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" =
height=3D"188" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"4320" data-file=
-height=3D"3240"></a><figcaption>An example of long division performed with=
out a calculator.</figcaption></figure>
<p>A more detailed breakdown of the steps goes as follows:
</p>
<ol><li>Find the shortest sequence of digits starting from the left end of =
the dividend, 500, that the divisor 4 goes into at least once. In this case=
, this is simply the first digit, 5. The largest number that the divisor 4 =
can be multiplied by without exceeding 5 is 1, so the digit 1 is put above =
the 5 to start constructing the quotient.</li>
<li>Next, the 1 is multiplied by the divisor 4, to obtain the largest whole=
 number that is a multiple of the divisor 4 without exceeding the 5 (4 in t=
his case). This 4 is then placed under and subtracted from the 5 to get the=
 remainder, 1, which is placed under the 4 under the 5.</li>
<li>Afterwards, the first as-yet unused digit in the dividend, in this case=
 the first digit 0 after the 5, is copied directly underneath itself and ne=
xt to the remainder 1, to form the number 10.</li>
<li>At this point the process is repeated enough times to reach a stopping =
point: The largest number by which the divisor 4 can be multiplied without =
exceeding 10 is 2, so 2 is written above as the second leftmost quotient di=
git. This 2 is then multiplied by the divisor 4 to get 8, which is the larg=
est multiple of 4 that does not exceed 10; so 8 is written below 10, and th=
e subtraction 10 minus 8 is performed to get the remainder 2, which is plac=
ed below the 8.</li>
<li>The next digit of the dividend (the last 0 in 500) is copied directly b=
elow itself and next to the remainder 2 to form 20. Then the largest number=
 by which the divisor 4 can be multiplied without exceeding 20, which is 5,=
 is placed above as the third leftmost quotient digit. This 5 is multiplied=
 by the divisor 4 to get 20, which is written below and subtracted from the=
 existing 20 to yield the remainder 0, which is then written below the seco=
nd 20.</li>
<li>At this point, since there are no more digits to bring down from the di=
vidend and the last subtraction result was 0, we can be assured that the pr=
ocess finished.</li></ol>
<p>If the last remainder when we ran out of dividend digits had been someth=
ing other than 0, there would have been two possible courses of action:
</p>
<ol><li>We could just stop there and say that the dividend divided by the d=
ivisor is the quotient written at the top with the remainder written at the=
 bottom, and write the answer as the quotient followed by a fraction that i=
s the remainder divided by the divisor.</li>
<li>We could extend the dividend by writing it as, say, 500.000... and cont=
inue the process (using a decimal point in the quotient directly above the =
decimal point in the dividend), in order to get a decimal answer, as in the=
 following example.</li></ol>
<pre>    <u>  31.75</u>    =20
   4)127.00
     <u>12</u>         (12 =C3=B7 4 =3D 3)
      07        (0 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Remainder" titl=
e=3D"Remainder">remainder</a>, bring down next figure)
       <u>4</u>        (7 =C3=B7 4 =3D 1 r 3)                              =
              =20
       3.0      (bring down 0 and the decimal point)
       <u>2.8</u>      (7 =C3=97 4 =3D 28, 30 =C3=B7 4 =3D 7 r 2)
         20     (an additional zero is brought down)
         <u>20</u>     (5 =C3=97 4 =3D 20)
          0
</pre>
<p>In this example, the decimal part of the result is calculated by continu=
ing the process beyond the units digit, "bringing down" zeros as being the =
decimal part of the dividend.
</p><p>This example also illustrates that, at the beginning of the process,=
 a step that produces a zero can be omitted.  Since the first digit 1 is le=
ss than the divisor 4, the first step is instead performed on the first two=
 digits 12.  Similarly, if the divisor were 13, one would perform the first=
 step on 127 rather than 12 or 1.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Basic_procedure_for_long_di=
vision_of_n_=C3=B7_m"><span id=3D"Basic_procedure_for_long_division_of_n_.C=
3.B7_m"></span>Basic procedure for long division of <span class=3D"texhtml"=
>n =C3=B7 m</span></h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?t=
itle=3DLong_division&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Basic procedure for long division of n =C3=B7 m"><span>edit</span></a><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<ol><li>Find the location of all decimal points in the dividend <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> and divisor <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span>.</li>
<li>If necessary, simplify the long division problem by moving the decimals=
 of the divisor and dividend by the same number of decimal places, to the r=
ight (or to the left), so that the decimal of the divisor is to the right o=
f the last digit.</li>
<li>When doing long division, keep the numbers lined up straight from top t=
o bottom under the tableau.</li>
<li>After each step, be sure the remainder for that step is less than the d=
ivisor. If it is not, there are three possible problems: the multiplication=
 is wrong, the subtraction is wrong, or a greater quotient is needed.</li>
<li>In the end, the remainder, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-s=
tyle:italic;">r</span>, is added to the growing quotient as a <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Fraction (mathematics)">fraction</a>, <span class=3D"frac"><span cl=
ass=3D"num">r</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">m</span></span>.</li></ol>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Invariant_property_and_corr=
ectness">Invariant property and correctness</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLong_division&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Invariant property and correctness"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The basic presentation of the steps of the process (above)
focus on the <i>what</i> steps are to be performed,
rather than the <i>properties of those steps</i> that ensure the result wil=
l be correct
(specifically, that <i>q =C3=97 m + r =3D n</i>, where <i>q</i> is the fina=
l quotient and <i>r</i> the final remainder).
A slight variation of presentation requires more writing,
and requires that we change, rather than just update, digits of the quotien=
t,
but can shed more light on <i>why</i> these steps actually produce the righ=
t answer
by allowing evaluation of <i>q =C3=97 m + r</i> at intermediate points in t=
he process.
This illustrates the key property used in the derivation of the algorithm=
=20
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_division#Algorithm_for_arbitr=
ary_base">(below)</a>.
</p><p>Specifically, we amend the above basic procedure so that
we fill the space after the digits of the <i>quotient</i> under constructio=
n with 0's, to at least the 1's place,
and include those 0's in the numbers we write below the division bracket.
</p><p>This lets us maintain an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In=
variant_(computer_science)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Invariant (compu=
ter science)">invariant relation</a> at every step:
<i>q =C3=97 m + r =3D n</i>, where <i>q</i> is the partially-constructed qu=
otient (above the division bracket)
and <i>r</i> the partially-constructed remainder (bottom number below the d=
ivision bracket).
Note that, initially <i>q=3D0</i> and <i>r=3Dn</i>, so this property holds =
initially;
the process reduces r and increases q with each step,
eventually stopping when <i>r&lt;m</i> if we seek the answer in quotient + =
integer remainder form.
</p><p>Revisiting the <i>500 =C3=B7 4</i> example above, we find
</p>
<pre>    <u> <span style=3D"color: red;">1</span><span style=3D"color: gree=
n;">2</span><span style=3D"color: blue;">5</span></u>      (<i>q</i>, chang=
es from 000 to <span style=3D"color: red;">100</span> to <span style=3D"col=
or: red;">1</span><span style=3D"color: green;">20</span> to <span style=3D=
"color: red;">1</span><span style=3D"color: green;">2</span><span style=3D"=
color: blue;">5</span> as per notes below)
   4)500
     <u>400</u>      (  4 =C3=97 <span style=3D"color: red;">100</span> =3D=
 400)
     <span style=3D"color: darkorange;">100</span>      (500 - 400 =3D <spa=
n style=3D"color: darkorange;">100</span>; now <i>q=3D<span style=3D"color:=
 red;">100</span></i>, <i>r=3D<span style=3D"color: darkorange;">100</span>=
</i>; note <i>q=C3=974+r =3D 500</i>.)
      <u>80</u>      (  4 =C3=97  <span style=3D"color: green;">20</span> =
=3D  80)
      <span style=3D"color: darkcyan;">20</span>      (100 -  80 =3D  <span=
 style=3D"color: darkcyan;">20</span>; now <i>q=3D<span style=3D"color: red=
;">1</span><span style=3D"color: green;">20</span></i>, <i>r=3D<span style=
=3D"color: darkcyan;"> 20</span></i>; note <i>q=C3=974+r =3D 500</i>.)
      <u>20</u>      (  4 =C3=97   <span style=3D"color: blue;">5</span> =
=3D  20)
       0      ( 20 -  20 =3D   0; now <i>q=3D<span style=3D"color: red;">1<=
/span><span style=3D"color: green;">2</span><span style=3D"color: blue;">5<=
/span></i>, <i>r=3D  0</i>; note <i>q=C3=974+r =3D 500</i>.)
</pre>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Example_with_multi-digit_di=
visor">Example with multi-digit divisor</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection">=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLong_division&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6=
" title=3D"Edit section: Example with multi-digit divisor"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:LongDivisionAnimated.gif" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikiped=
ia/commons/f/f2/LongDivisionAnimated.gif" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"116" =
height=3D"200" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"116" data-file-=
height=3D"200"></a><figcaption>Animated example of multi-digit long divisio=
n</figcaption></figure>
<p>A divisor of any number of digits can be used. In this example, 1260257 =
is to be divided by 37. First the problem is set up as follows:
</p>
<pre>       <u>       </u>
    37)1260257
</pre>
<p>Digits of the number 1260257 are taken until a number greater than or eq=
ual to 37 occurs. So 1 and 12 are less than 37, but 126 is greater. Next, t=
he greatest multiple of 37 less than or equal to 126 is computed. So 3 =C3=
=97 37 =3D 111 &lt; 126, but 4 =C3=97 37 &gt; 126. The multiple 111 is writ=
ten underneath the 126 and the 3 is written on the top where the solution w=
ill appear:
</p>
<pre>       <u>  3    </u>
    37)1260257
       111
</pre>
<p>Note carefully which place-value column these digits are written into. T=
he 3 in the quotient goes in the same column (ten-thousands place) as the 6=
 in the dividend 1260257, which is the same column as the last digit of 111=
.
</p><p>The 111 is then subtracted from the line above, ignoring all digits =
to the right:
</p>
<pre>       <u>  3    </u>
    37)1260257
       <u>111</u>
        15
</pre>
<p>Now the digit from the next smaller place value of the dividend is copie=
d down and appended to the result 15:
</p>
<pre>       <u>  3    </u>
    37)1260257
       <u>111</u>
        150
</pre>
<p>The process repeats: the greatest multiple of 37 less than or equal to 1=
50 is subtracted. This is 148 =3D 4 =C3=97 37, so a 4 is added to the top a=
s the next quotient digit. Then the result of the subtraction is extended b=
y another digit taken from the dividend:
</p>
<pre>       <u>  34   </u>
    37)1260257
       <u>111</u>
        150
        <u>148</u>
          22
</pre>
<p>The greatest multiple of 37 less than or equal to 22 is 0 =C3=97 37 =3D =
0. Subtracting 0 from 22 gives 22, we often don't write the subtraction ste=
p. Instead, we simply take another digit from the dividend:
</p>
<pre>       <u>  340  </u>
    37)1260257
       <u>111</u>
        150
        <u>148</u>
          225
</pre>
<p>The process is repeated until 37 divides the last line exactly:
</p>
<pre>       <u>  34061</u>
    37)1260257
       <u>111</u>
        150
        <u>148</u>
          225
          <u>222</u>
            37
</pre>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Mixed_mode_long_division">M=
ixed mode long division</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DLong_division&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit =
section: Mixed mode long division"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>For non-decimal currencies (such as the British <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/%C2%A3sd" title=3D"=C2=A3sd">=C2=A3sd</a> system before 19=
71) and measures (such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avoirdup=
ois" title=3D"Avoirdupois">avoirdupois</a>) <b>mixed mode</b> division must=
 be used.  Consider dividing 50 miles 600 yards into 37 pieces:
</p>
<pre>          mi -     yd -   ft -   in
      <u>     1 -    634      1      9 r. 15"</u>
    37)   50 -    600 -    0 -    0
          <u>37</u>    <u>22880</u>     <u>66</u>    <u>348</u>
          13    23480     66    348
        <u>1760</u>    <u>222</u>       <u>37</u>    <u>333</u>
       22880     128      <u>29</u>     15
       =3D=3D=3D=3D=3D     <u>111</u>     348     =3D=3D
                  170    =3D=3D=3D
                  <u>148</u>
                   <u>22</u>
                   66
                   =3D=3D
</pre>
<p>Each of the four columns is worked in turn.  Starting with the miles: 50=
/37 =3D 1 remainder 13.  No further division is
possible, so perform a long multiplication by 1,760 to convert miles to yar=
ds, the result is 22,880 yards.  Carry this to the top of the yards column =
and add it to the 600 yards in the dividend giving 23,480.  Long division o=
f 23,480 / 37 now proceeds as normal yielding 634 with remainder 22.  The r=
emainder is multiplied by 3 to get feet and carried up to the feet column. =
 Long division of the feet gives 1 remainder 29 which is then multiplied by=
 twelve to get 348 inches.  Long division continues with the final remainde=
r of 15 inches being shown on the result line.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Interpretation_of_decimal_r=
esults">Interpretation of decimal results</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLong_division&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Interpretation of decimal results"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>When the quotient is not an integer and the division process is extended=
 beyond the decimal point, one of two things can happen:
</p>
<ol><li>The process can terminate, which means that a remainder of 0 is rea=
ched; or</li>
<li>A remainder could be reached that is identical to a previous remainder =
that occurred after the decimal points were written. In the latter case, co=
ntinuing the process would be pointless, because from that point onward the=
 same sequence of digits would appear in the quotient over and over. So a b=
ar is drawn over the repeating sequence to indicate that it repeats forever=
 (i.e., <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Repeating_decimal#Every_ra=
tional_number_is_either_a_terminating_or_repeating_decimal" title=3D"Repeat=
ing decimal">every rational number is either a terminating or repeating dec=
imal</a>).</li></ol>
