<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Generalizations">Generaliza=
tions</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLong_d=
ivision&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: Generali=
zations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Rational_numbers">Rational =
numbers</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLong=
_division&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: Ration=
al numbers"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<p>Long division of integers can easily be extended to include non-integer =
dividends, as long as they are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rat=
ional_number" title=3D"Rational number">rational</a>. This is because every=
 rational number has a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recurring_d=
ecimal" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Recurring decimal">recurring decimal=
</a> expansion. The procedure can also be extended to include divisors whic=
h have a finite or terminating <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dec=
imal" title=3D"Decimal">decimal</a> expansion (i.e. <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Decimal_fraction" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Decimal =
fraction">decimal fractions</a>). In this case the procedure involves multi=
plying the divisor and dividend by the appropriate power of ten so that the=
 new divisor is an integer&nbsp;=E2=80=93 taking advantage of the fact that=
 <i>a</i>&nbsp;=C3=B7&nbsp;<i>b</i> =3D (<i>ca</i>)&nbsp;=C3=B7&nbsp;(<i>cb=
</i>)&nbsp;=E2=80=93  and then proceeding as above.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Polynomials">Polynomials</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLong_division&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit section: Polynomials"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<p>A generalised version of this method called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Polynomial_long_division" title=3D"Polynomial long division">p=
olynomial long division</a> is also used for dividing <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial" title=3D"Polynomial">polynomials</a> (somet=
imes using a shorthand version called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Synthetic_division" title=3D"Synthetic division">synthetic division</a>=
).
</p>
